cess sound—to pragmatically comprehend the representational excesses that data produces. Writing at a cultural moment in which data has never been more ubiquitous or less convincing, Cecchetto elucidates the paradoxes that are constitutive of computation and communication more broadly, demonstrating that data is never quite what it seems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunication and technologyxPhilosophy. 0aCommunication and technologyxSocial aspects. 0aCommunication and the artsxPhilosophy. 0aSound (Philosophy) 0aSound (Philosophy). 0aTechnologyxPhilosophy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076691240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478022534?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478022534423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478022534/original  a978-3-11-076691-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles